CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION

1.1 Background of Study
Final Year Project supervision is a structured academic process that involves planning, regular consultations, milestone tracking, feedback cycles, and final evaluation. In many institutions, this process is still handled through fragmented tools such as messaging apps, spreadsheets, paper forms, and manual records.

As the number of students and supervisors increases, these traditional practices create difficulties in coordination and monitoring. Students may miss deadlines due to unclear tracking, supervisors may face workload management issues, and administrators may struggle to obtain reliable progress reports.

The growth of web technologies and cloud-based collaboration tools creates an opportunity to modernize this process. A centralized web-based system can provide better accessibility, consistent documentation, and real-time communication. Integrating analytics and intelligent features can further improve supervision quality and project outcomes.

1.2 Problem Statements
The current FYP management approach faces several practical challenges:
1. Fragmented communication channels.
2. Poor visibility of student progress.
3. Manual and inconsistent record keeping.
4. Limited support for academic writing and research tasks.
5. Lack of integrated reporting and decision support.

1.3 Objective
General Objective:
To develop a web-based FYP Management System that improves supervision workflow, communication, and progress monitoring for students, supervisors, and university administrators.

Specific Objectives:
- Implement secure role-based access for different user groups.
- Provide structured supervision session and feedback management.
- Support real-time communication and reminder mechanisms.
- Visualize project progress through charts and dashboard indicators.
- Integrate AI-based assistance for academic queries and summarization.
- Generate useful reporting outputs for institutional monitoring.

1.4 Scope of Study
Included scope:
- Web platform for FYP-related processes.
- User roles: student, supervisor, university administrator.
- Modules: authentication, user management, sessions, reminders, chat, analytics, integrations.
- AI features: chatbot guidance and research summarization support.
- Responsive browser-based interface.

Excluded scope:
- Native mobile application.
- Full integration with all legacy university systems.
- Full plagiarism detection and automated grading engine.

1.5 Project Feasibility
Technical Feasibility:
The project is feasible due to mature web technologies and modular microservices architecture.

Operational Feasibility:
The platform aligns with existing academic supervision workflows and is easy to adopt.

Economic Feasibility:
Open-source tools reduce implementation and maintenance costs.

Schedule Feasibility:
A phased plan with milestones supports completion within an academic timeline.


CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE REVIEW

2.1 Event Management
Event management in academic systems refers to planning, scheduling, and tracking time-based activities such as supervision meetings, proposal reviews, reminders, and submission deadlines. Effective event management improves coordination and reduces missed milestones.

2.2 Usability Features
Usability is critical in educational platforms. Main attributes include learnability, efficiency, memorability, error prevention, and user satisfaction. For supervision systems, usability strongly affects adoption by students and faculty.

2.2.1 Benefits of web-based system
- Accessibility from anywhere via browser.
- Centralized records and better consistency.
- Real-time updates for reminders and status.
- Lower maintenance from centralized deployment.
- Better scalability for future growth.

2.3 Understanding graphic presentation on web-based system
Visual analytics (charts, progress bars, dashboards) helps users quickly interpret project status, identify delays, and prioritize tasks. In FYP supervision, it improves student self-monitoring and advisor decision-making.

2.4 Comparison between Available Technologies in the Market
Existing options include generic task tools, LMS platforms, and custom institutional systems. Generic tools are flexible but less academic-specific; LMS platforms are course-focused; custom platforms offer better fit but require stronger design and maintenance planning.

2.5 Designing Effective Web System
Key design principles from literature:
1. Role-based workflow design.
2. Modular architecture.
3. Data consistency and auditability.
4. Interactive and responsive UI.
5. Integrated communication and analytics.
6. Practical AI assistance for academic support.

